{
  "text": "Large-scale genomic changes such as chromosomal rearrangements and aneuploidy can also drive the emergence of fluconazole resistance. In particular, formation of an isochromosome comprising the two left arms of Chr5 (i5L) confers high levels of resistance to azole drugs in C. albicans [CITATION_1] . The left arm of Chr5 encodes both the fluconazole target Erg11 and the transcription factor Tac1. Elevated expression of these genes due to increased copy number in strains carrying i5L mediates increased drug resistance [CITATION_2] . Changes in the complement of chromosomes have also been associated with drug resistance in other fungal pathogens [CITATION_3] . In general, the emergence of aneuploid forms provides a way for cells to rapidly generate genotypic and phenotypic diversity without permanently committing to the mutant genotype [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] . This rapid but imperfect mechanism of adaptation can subsequently be replaced by more refined adaptive changes that have a lower fitness cost [CITATION_7] .",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "31732276",
